# GUIDE TO WRITING YOUR INTERNSHIP LOGBOOK

## What is a logbook?

The logbook is a tool that allows you to record your reflections, your comments, and your questions… throughout your internship.

## Why write in a logbook?

To become aware of your learning and the skills you use in a work situation.
Your logbook is the “memory” of your learning!

## When should you write in your logbook?

Several possibilities:

* At the end of each week (to review the week’s different tasks and activities)
* Every day (2 or 3 sentences about your main learnings and daily activities)
* Every 2 weeks (review of activities and missions carried out)

## What should you write in your logbook?

Here are some ideas/prompts to help you write your logbook:

* What did I learn?
* What missions did I accomplish?
* What skills/know-how did I use to complete my missions?
* What difficulties did I face? What solutions did I provide?
* What challenge(s) am I facing during the internship? How am I dealing with them?
* How do I organize myself to successfully complete each mission (task distribution, managing deadlines for deliverables, etc.)?
* Is my internship consistent with the idea I had of the job/sector? If not, why?

👉 Always give concrete examples of your achievements, skills, and difficulties.

---

## Example:

“My internship supervisor asked me to lead a work meeting on the communication project I am involved in. I learned how to organize a work session: finding a suitable date in everyone’s schedule, booking a meeting room, preparing an agenda, introducing the topics at the beginning of the meeting, taking notes to write the report, ensuring fair speaking time for everyone, summarizing the main ideas that emerge, and asking relevant questions according to the announced agenda.

I enjoy communicating, and I realize that I am comfortable speaking in public. I really had to be organized to manage the meeting.

However, I found it difficult to lead the meeting because sometimes some people dominated the discussion, preventing others from speaking. It was my role to ensure balanced participation, so I sometimes had to be firm to give others the opportunity to speak.”